My morning routine has developed over the years. Most recently, I’ve adopted the habit of reading a passage from one of my favorite daily readers while I brush my teeth. It’s usually no more than a page, and sometimes I’ll read it twice to allow the words to really sink in. It fills the time, and I’m more likely to spend the full two minutes brushing rather than rushing through the mundane task—for which my teeth (and dentist) are appreciative.

This morning’s passage was about not holding onto our mistakes of the past. It’s uncomfortable revisiting the times when we weren’t our best selves—reflecting with honesty and kindness. We’ve all been there. Maybe you were having a bad day and spoke unkindly to the barista when they forgot your order during the busy morning rush. Perhaps you cut someone off in traffic because you were stressed about being late for work. Or maybe you said something you didn’t mean to a loved one because you were carrying more than you realized—of that, I’m guilty.

I took inventory this morning of the past week, and it was easy to recall the things I felt guilty about. I could see where I went wrong and how I might have brought a different energy to each situation. I could see how my poor demeanor was souring moments not only for myself, but for the people I came into contact with. I considered how I would feel being on the receiving end.

For the past three months, I’ve been attending a weekly group. Every Wednesday evening, we—a group of otherwise strangers brought together by one common thread—meet and discuss how we’re doing. We take moral inventory. Through the collective consciousness of the group, I’ve been able to explore facets of myself I’d been too afraid to look at. The parts of me I couldn’t admit to.

Controlling? Never.  
People pleaser? As if.  
Perfectionist? No way.

At first, I thought, *gosh, this is uncomfortable.* Broadcasting out loud to the group the laundry list of things I’m ashamed of. It felt uncomfortable, and the words tasted bitter coming out of my mouth. I could hardly look at the people I was talking to, so I spent my time speaking to ten pairs of shoes. When I finally looked up, I was caught off guard. I saw people smiling and nodding in agreement. I felt light.

Once my turn was over—thank goodness—the next person spoke. As I listened, I thought, *this person is speaking my truths.* By the time we got to the last person, I had heard nine variations of my own story. And not once did I cast judgment on anyone. I could empathize. I walked away with a refreshed perspective. I’m not a bad person. Sometimes I make mistakes, but being able to reflect on those mistakes, learn from them, and have the wisdom to choose to act differently next time is golden.

Through my experience at these weekly meetings, I’ve become more comfortable admitting to myself—and to others—that I am human. I am messy. I make mistakes. I say things I don’t mean. I get overwhelmed. And I continue to learn—and that’s fantastic. My past doesn’t define me. Tomorrow is a new day, and through my experiences, I’ve gained the wisdom to choose a different path.
